{"title_page": "New Barnet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead too short|date=August 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2008}}\n}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name=New Barnet, Station Approach - geograph.org.uk - 151046.jpg\n|static_image_caption=Station Approach, New Barnet\n|country = England\n|map_type = Greater London\n|region= London\n|population=\n|official_name= New Barnet\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.6440|-0.1708|display=inline,title}}\n|constituency_westminster= [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]]\n|post_town= BARNET\n|postcode_area=EN\n|postcode_district= EN4, EN5\n|london_borough= Barnet \n|dial_code= 020\n|os_grid_reference= TQ265955\n}}\n'''New Barnet''' is a area within the [[London Borough of Barnet]]. It is a largely residential [[North London]] [[suburb]], close to the [[M25 motorway|M25]], [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] and [[M1 motorway|M1]]. It is located east of [[Chipping Barnet]], west of [[Cockfosters]], south of [[Monken Hadley]] and north of [[Oakleigh Park]].\n\n{{TOC left|limit=|width=}}\nThe main commercial area in New Barnet is on ''East Barnet Road'', near the railway station. A large [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket (opened in 1980) is surrounded by a cluster of small independent shops. Other shops and facilities include Fayers, Just Add Water, [[PureGym]], Tesco Express, [[Majestic Wine]], The Party Shop, Bikestrobe, Ink n Toner and Bodens Performing Arts. A number of office blocks were built in ''Station Road'' in the 1960s & 70s. Some have now been converted to flats. In the past Station Approach in New Barnet was the home of CompShop which produced the pioneering [[UK101]] kit [[microcomputer]]. Several Cafes also exist on the High Street. \n\nHousing includes a mix of late Victorian villas, terraces, Edwardian detached housing, 1950 - 1960s council housing and the redevelopment of land to low storey flats in the 1980s and 1990s.\n\nPublic Houses in New Barnet include ''The Railway Tavern'', ''The Railway Bell'' ([[Wetherspoons]]) ''The Builders Arms'' and ''The Lord Kitchener''.\n\nChurches include: ''Anglican'' St James's (East Barnet Road), [[St Mark's Church, Barnet Vale|St Mark's]] (Potters Road), Holy Trinity (Corner of Lyonsdown and Somerset Roads); ''Catholic'' Mary Immaculate & St Peter (Somerset Road); ''United Reformed Church'' [http://www.stjohnsnewbarnet.org.uk St John's] (Corner of Somerset and Mowbray Roads); ''Quaker'' Friends' Meeting (Leicester Road).\n\n[[File:Victoria Recreation Ground - New Barnet.jpg|alt=|thumb|Victoria Recreation Ground]]\n\n\n\n==History==\nNew Barnet owes its conception to the building of the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] in 1850, when a station serving High Barnet was built, but located about a mile away from the town centre of High Barnet, so that this 'new' area quickly saw development. \n\nIn 1876, ''Handbook to the Environs of London'' by James Thorne describe New Barnet as \u201cone of those new half-finished railway villages that we have come to look on as almost a necessary adjunct of every station within a moderate distance of London.\u201d\n\nNew Barnet's growth accelerated at the turn of the 19th Century aided by the speculative developer, [[E. Fergusson Taylor]], who became know as the \"creator of New Barnet\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hidden-london.com/gazetteer/new-barnet/|title=New Barnet {{!}} Hidden London|website=hidden-london.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1894 New Barnet formed part of the [[East Barnet Urban District]] of [[Hertfordshire]] until 1965 when it was [[List of Hertfordshire boundary changes|transferred from Hertfordshire]] to [[Greater London]] to become part of the newly created [[London Borough of Barnet]]. The former town hall still stands in [[Station Road, New Barnet|Station Road]]. Local government use ended in the early 1990s and the property was sold off for use as a restaurant. In 2006 the building was converted into flats.\n\nIn 2019 a new Leisure Centre in New Barnet was completed by Barnet council including a 25m pool and gym. The Leisure Centre is run by the not-for-profit provider Better.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisislocallondon.co.uk/news/17892598.new-barnet-leisure-centre-officially-opens-public/|title=State-of-the-art leisure centre officially opened to public|website=This Is Local London|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n[[File:New Barnet Leisure Centre.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Transport==\n===Trains===\nThe main serving Rail Station in the area is [[New Barnet railway station|New Barnet Station]] ([[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]]).\n\n[[File:New Barnet Rail Station.jpg|thumb|New Barnet Rail Station]]\n\nRegular Trains run south into London Moorgate via Finsbury Park and North to Welwyn Garden City via Potters Bar. \n\nThe closest Tube Stations are [[High Barnet tube station]] to the West and [[Cockfosters tube station]] to the East. \n===Buses===\nBuses serving New Barnet are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"width:10%;\" |'''Route'''\n| style=\"width:30%;\" |'''Start'''\n| style=\"width:30%;\" |'''End'''\n| style=\"width:20%;\" |'''Operator'''\n|-\n|[[Hertfordshire bus route 84|84]]<br>''not a London bus route''\n|[[New Barnet railway station]]\n|[[St Albans]]\n|[[Metroline]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 107|107]]\n|[[New Barnet railway station]]\n|[[Edgware]]\n|Metroline\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 184|184]]\n|Ducks Island, Barnet\n|[[Turnpike Lane tube station|Turnpike Lane Station]]\n|[[Arriva London]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 307|307]]\n|[[Barnet Hospital]]\n|[[Brimsdown]]\n|[[Arriva London]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 326|326]]\n|[[The Spires Shopping Centre]], Barnet\n|[[Brent Cross]]\n|[[London Sovereign]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 383|383]]\n|[[The Spires Shopping Centre]], Barnet\n|[[Woodside Park]]\n|[[Uno (bus company)]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 384|384]]\n|[[Arkley]]\n|[[Cockfosters tube station]]\n|Metroline\n|-\n|714\n|New Barnet\n|[[Luton]] via [[Luton Airport]]\n|Metroline<ref>{{cite web|title = Route 714 New Barnet - St Albans - Luton Airport - Luton|url = http://www.metroline.co.uk/routes/coming-soon-new-route-714-barnet---luton.html|website = Metroline|accessdate = 2015-06-30|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150531011153/http://www.metroline.co.uk/routes/coming-soon-new-route-714-barnet---luton.html|archivedate = 2015-05-31}}</ref>\n|} \n\n==Schools==\n===Primary===\n\n* Livingstone School\n* Cromer Road School\n* Trent School\n* Lyonsdown School ([[Independent school (UK)|Independent]]) 49 in top 100 primary schools\n\n===Secondary===\n\n*[[Jewish Community Secondary School]] ('''Jcoss''')\n* East Barnet School ('''EBS''')\n\n==Governance ==\n[[Barnet local elections]] are held every four years to elect Councillors to [[Barnet London Borough Council]]. New Barnet is covered by three [[Wards of the United Kingdom|wards]]:\n\n*''East Barnet Ward''\n*''High Barnet Ward''\n*''Oakleigh Ward''\n\nNew Barnet is in the [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)]] and is represented by the [[Conservative Party (UK)]] MP [[Theresa Villiers]]. \n\n==See also==\n\n*[[John Sebastian Marlowe Ward]] who founded a folk museum in Park Road.\n{{Geographic Location\n|title = '''Neighbouring areas'''\n|Northwest = [[Monken Hadley]]\n|North = [[Hadley Wood]]\n|Northeast = [[Cockfosters]]\n|West = [[High Barnet]]\n|Centre = New Barnet\n|East = [[East Barnet]]\n|Southwest = [[Whetstone, London|Whetstone]]\n|South = [[Oakleigh Park]]\n|Southeast = [[Osidge]]\n}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|New Barnet}}\n{{LB Barnet}}{{Areas of London}}\n\n[[Category:New Barnet| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead too short|date=August 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2008}}\n}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name=New Barnet, Station Approach - geograph.org.uk - 151046.jpg\n|static_image_caption=Station Approach, New Barnet\n|country = England\n|map_type = Greater London\n|region= London\n|population=\n|official_name= New Barnet\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.6440|-0.1708|display=inline,title}}\n|constituency_westminster= [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]]\n|post_town= BARNET\n|postcode_area=EN\n|postcode_district= EN4, EN5\n|london_borough= Barnet \n|dial_code= 020\n|os_grid_reference= TQ265955\n}}\n'''New Barnet''' is a area within the [[London Borough of Barnet]]. It is a largely residential [[North London]] [[suburb]], close to the [[M25 motorway|M25]], [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] and [[M1 motorway|M1]]. It is located east of [[Chipping Barnet]], west of [[Cockfosters]], south of [[Monken Hadley]] and north of [[Oakleigh Park]].\n\n{{TOC left|limit=|width=}}\nThe main commercial area in New Barnet is on ''East Barnet Road'', near the railway station. A large [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket (opened in 1980) is surrounded by a cluster of small independent shops. Other shops and facilities include Fayers, Just Add Water, [[PureGym]], Tesco Express, [[Majestic Wine]], The Party Shop, Bikestrobe, Ink n Toner and Bodens Performing Arts. A number of office blocks were built in ''Station Road'' in the 1960s & 70s. Some have now been converted to flats. In the past Station Approach in New Barnet was the home of CompShop which produced the pioneering [[UK101]] kit [[microcomputer]]. Several Cafes also exist on the High Street. \n\nHousing includes a mix of late Victorian villas, terraces, Edwardian detached housing, 1950 - 1960s council housing and the redevelopment of land to low storey flats in the 1980s and 1990s.\n\nPublic Houses in New Barnet include ''The Railway Tavern'', ''The Railway Bell'' ([[Wetherspoons]]) ''The Builders Arms'' and ''The Lord Kitchener''.\n\nChurches include: ''Anglican'' St James's (East Barnet Road), [[St Mark's Church, Barnet Vale|St Mark's]] (Potters Road), Holy Trinity (Corner of Lyonsdown and Somerset Roads); ''Catholic'' Mary Immaculate & St Peter (Somerset Road); ''United Reformed Church'' [http://www.stjohnsnewbarnet.org.uk St John's] (Corner of Somerset and Mowbray Roads); ''Quaker'' Friends' Meeting (Leicester Road).\n\n[[File:Victoria Recreation Ground - New Barnet.jpg|alt=|thumb|Victoria Recreation Ground]]\n\n\n\n==History==\nNew Barnet owes its conception to the building of the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] in 1850, when a station serving High Barnet was built, but located about a mile away from the town centre of High Barnet, so that this 'new' area quickly saw development. \n\nIn 1876, ''Handbook to the Environs of London'' by James Thorne describe New Barnet as \u201cone of those new half-finished railway villages that we have come to look on as almost a necessary adjunct of every station within a moderate distance of London.\u201d\n\nNew Barnet's growth accelerated at the turn of the 19th Century aided by the speculative developer, [[E. Fergusson Taylor]], who became know as the the \"creator of New Barnet\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hidden-london.com/gazetteer/new-barnet/|title=New Barnet {{!}} Hidden London|website=hidden-london.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1894 New Barnet formed part of the [[East Barnet Urban District]] of [[Hertfordshire]] until 1965 when it was [[List of Hertfordshire boundary changes|transferred from Hertfordshire]] to [[Greater London]] to become part of the newly created [[London Borough of Barnet]]. The former town hall still stands in [[Station Road, New Barnet|Station Road]]. Local government use ended in the early 1990s and the property was sold off for use as a restaurant. In 2006 the building was converted into flats.\n\nIn 2019 a new Leisure Centre in New Barnet was completed by Barnet council including a 25m pool and gym. The Leisure Centre is run by the not-for-profit provider Better.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisislocallondon.co.uk/news/17892598.new-barnet-leisure-centre-officially-opens-public/|title=State-of-the-art leisure centre officially opened to public|website=This Is Local London|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n[[File:New Barnet Leisure Centre.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Transport==\n===Trains===\nThe main serving Rail Station in the area is [[New Barnet railway station|New Barnet Station]] ([[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]]).\n\n[[File:New Barnet Rail Station.jpg|thumb|New Barnet Rail Station]]\n\nRegular Trains run south into London Moorgate via Finsbury Park and North to Welwyn Garden City via Potters Bar. \n\nThe closest Tube Stations are [[High Barnet tube station]] to the West and [[Cockfosters tube station]] to the East. \n===Buses===\nBuses serving New Barnet are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"width:10%;\" |'''Route'''\n| style=\"width:30%;\" |'''Start'''\n| style=\"width:30%;\" |'''End'''\n| style=\"width:20%;\" |'''Operator'''\n|-\n|[[Hertfordshire bus route 84|84]]<br>''not a London bus route''\n|[[New Barnet railway station]]\n|[[St Albans]]\n|[[Metroline]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 107|107]]\n|[[New Barnet railway station]]\n|[[Edgware]]\n|Metroline\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 184|184]]\n|Ducks Island, Barnet\n|[[Turnpike Lane tube station|Turnpike Lane Station]]\n|[[Arriva London]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 307|307]]\n|[[Barnet Hospital]]\n|[[Brimsdown]]\n|[[Arriva London]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 326|326]]\n|[[The Spires Shopping Centre]], Barnet\n|[[Brent Cross]]\n|[[London Sovereign]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 383|383]]\n|[[The Spires Shopping Centre]], Barnet\n|[[Woodside Park]]\n|[[Uno (bus company)]]\n|-\n|[[London Buses route 384|384]]\n|[[Arkley]]\n|[[Cockfosters tube station]]\n|Metroline\n|-\n|714\n|New Barnet\n|[[Luton]] via [[Luton Airport]]\n|Metroline<ref>{{cite web|title = Route 714 New Barnet - St Albans - Luton Airport - Luton|url = http://www.metroline.co.uk/routes/coming-soon-new-route-714-barnet---luton.html|website = Metroline|accessdate = 2015-06-30|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150531011153/http://www.metroline.co.uk/routes/coming-soon-new-route-714-barnet---luton.html|archivedate = 2015-05-31}}</ref>\n|} \n\n==Schools==\n===Primary===\n\n* Livingstone School\n* Cromer Road School\n* Trent School\n* Lyonsdown School ([[Independent school (UK)|Independent]]) 49 in top 100 primary schools\n\n===Secondary===\n\n*[[Jewish Community Secondary School]] ('''Jcoss''')\n* East Barnet School ('''EBS''')\n\n==Governance ==\n[[Barnet local elections]] are held every four years to elect Councillors to [[Barnet London Borough Council]]. New Barnet is covered by three [[Wards of the United Kingdom|wards]]:\n\n*''East Barnet Ward''\n*''High Barnet Ward''\n*''Oakleigh Ward''\n\nNew Barnet is in the [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)]] and is represented by the [[Conservative Party (UK)]] MP [[Theresa Villiers]]. \n\n==See also==\n\n*[[John Sebastian Marlowe Ward]] who founded a folk museum in Park Road.\n{{Geographic Location\n|title = '''Neighbouring areas'''\n|Northwest = [[Monken Hadley]]\n|North = [[Hadley Wood]]\n|Northeast = [[Cockfosters]]\n|West = [[High Barnet]]\n|Centre = New Barnet\n|East = [[East Barnet]]\n|Southwest = [[Whetstone, London|Whetstone]]\n|South = [[Oakleigh Park]]\n|Southeast = [[Osidge]]\n}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|New Barnet}}\n{{LB Barnet}}{{Areas of London}}\n\n[[Category:New Barnet| ]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Barnet"}
{"title_page": "Ringtone (Remix)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name     = Ringtone (Remix)\n| cover    = Ringtone Remix cover art.jpg\n| border   = \n| alt      = Dylan Brady and Laura Les wear black robes and hold a mirror.\n| type     = single\n| artist   = [[100 Gecs]] featuring [[Charli XCX]], [[Rico Nasty]] and [[Kero Kero Bonito]]\n| album    = [[1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues]]\n| released = {{Start date|2020|2|24}}\n| format   =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| length   = {{Duration|m=3|s=35}}\n| label    = Dog Show\n| chronology = [[100 Gecs]]\n| prev_title = 745 Sticky (Injury Reserve Remix)\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = gec 2 \u00dc (Remix)\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc = {{Extra chronology \n| artist = [[Charli XCX]]\n| type = single\n| prev_title = Bricks\n| prev_year = 2019\n| title = Ringtone (Remix)\n| year = 2020\n| next_title = Bricks\n| next_year = 2020}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = [[Rico Nasty]]\n| type = single\n| prev_title = IDGAF\n| prev_year = 2020\n| title = Ringtone (Remix)\n| year = 2020\n| next_title = Lightning\n| next_year = 2020\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = [[Kero Kero Bonito]]\n| type = single\n| prev_title = When the Fires Come\n| prev_year = 2019\n| title = Ringtone (Remix)\n| year = 2020\n| next_title = \n| next_year = \n}}\n{{External music video|header=Visualizer video|{{YouTube|OmX4UPiVS-w|\"Ringtone (Remix)\"}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Ringtone (Remix).ogg}}\n}}\n\"'''Ringtone (Remix)'''\" is a song by American experimental musical duo [[100 Gecs]], composed of Dylan Brady and Laura Les, from their upcoming remix album ''[[1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues]]'' (2020). The song features [[Guest appearance|featured vocals]] from British singer [[Charli XCX]], American rapper [[Rico Nasty]], and British indie pop band [[Kero Kero Bonito]]. The song is a remix of \"Ringtone\", a highlight from 100 Gecs' debut studio album ''[[1000 Gecs]]'' (2019). The song's production is glitchy with \"[[1980s in video games|80's video game]]-inspired blips\" and uses heavy [[Bass (sound)|bass]] and [[Auto-Tune]]. \n\n\"Ringtone (Remix)\" was first previewed at a live DJ set in January 2020. It was released a month later on February 24, 2020 as the third single from ''1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues'', following the release of the \"Money Machine\" and \"745 Sticky\" remixes. The song was met with critical acclaim, who praised Charli XCX's guest appearance.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Charlixcxnoodles.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Brady previously worked with British singer [[Charli XCX]] (pictured), whose guest appearance on \"Ringtone (Remix)\" was praised by critics.]]\n100 Gecs released their debut album, ''[[1000 Gecs]]'', on May 31, 2019. Jillian Mapes of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called the original version of \"Ringtone\" as a highlight from the album and \"among 100 Gecs' catchiest songs.\"<ref name=\"p4k\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-ft-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-and-kero-kero-bonito|title=\"ringtone (Remix)\" by 100 gecs Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Jillian Mapes|date=February 25, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229023901/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-ft-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-and-kero-kero-bonito|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Brady produced on British singer [[Charli XCX]]'s song \"[[Click (Charli XCX song)|Click]]\" featuring German singer [[Kim Petras]] and Estonian rapper [[Tommy Cash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/117418368/credits|title=Credits / Charli / Charli XCX \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> \"Click\" was included on Charli XCX's third studio album ''[[Charli (album)|Charli]]'', released on September 13, 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/46001/1/listen-to-charli-xcx-new-album-charli|title=It\u2019s here! Listen to Charli XCX\u2019s new album, Charli|website=[[Dazed]]|author=Gunseli Yalcinkaya|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401024956/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/46001/1/listen-to-charli-xcx-new-album-charli|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and was later rereleased as \"Click (No Boys Remix)\" that replaces Cash with American singer [[Slayyyter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8532958/charli-xcx-kim-petras-slayyyter-for-click-remix|title=Charli XCX Teams Up With Kim Petras & Slayyyter for 'No Boys' Remix of 'Click': Listen|author=October 14, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301194509/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8532958/charli-xcx-kim-petras-slayyyter-for-click-remix|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2019, 100 Gecs announced an upcoming remix album titled ''1000 Gecs & Th3 Phant0m M3nac3''.<ref name=\"AG\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/100-gecs-announce-new-remix-album-share-a-g-cook-money-machine-listen|title=100 gecs Announce New Remix Album, Share A. G. Cook\u2019s \"money machine\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Matthew Strauss|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229023905/https://pitchfork.com/news/100-gecs-announce-new-remix-album-share-a-g-cook-money-machine-listen|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A remix of \"Money Machine\" by British producer [[A. G. Cook]] was released alongside the announcement.<ref name=\"AG\"/> A. G. Cook is a frequent Charli XCX collaborator.<ref name=\"p4k\"/> On November 6, 2019, 100 Gecs released a remix of \"745 Sticky\" with American hip hop trio [[Injury Reserve]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/11/06/injury-reserve-remix-100-gecs-745-sticky|title=Listen to Injury Reserve\u2019s new remix of 100 gecs' \"745 Sticky\"|website=[[The Fader]]|author=Jack Denton|date=November 6, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211205826/https://www.thefader.com/2019/11/06/injury-reserve-remix-100-gecs-745-sticky|archive-date=December 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, American rapper [[Rico Nasty]] teased an upcoming collaboration with Brady titled \"iPhone\"; Nasty said in January 2020 that she'd release the song once American rapper [[Lil Uzi Vert]] recorded a verse for it.<ref name=\"Paper\">{{Cite web|url=http://papermag.com/dylan-brady-rico-nasty-track-2645128012.html|title=The Stans Demand Rico Nasty and Dylan Brady's Collabs|website=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|date=February 12, 2020|author=Brendan Wetmore|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311142024/https://www.papermag.com/dylan-brady-rico-nasty-track-2645128012.html|archive-date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Upon the release of \"Ringtone (Remix)\", the remix album was renamed ''1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/charli-xcx-and-rico-nasty-join-100-gecs-on-new-ringtone-remix-listen|title=Charli XCX and Rico Nasty Join 100 gecs on New \"ringtone (remix)\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Allison Hussey|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302195312/https://pitchfork.com/news/charli-xcx-and-rico-nasty-join-100-gecs-on-new-ringtone-remix-listen|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\"Ringtone (Remix)\" is less frenzied than its original counterpart and fits with Charli XCX's futuristic pop style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/stream-100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|title=Charli XCX and Rico Nasty Join 100 gecs on New \u201cringtone\u201d Remix: Stream|author=Lake Schatz|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225131914/https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/stream-100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Brendan Wetmore of ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' wrote that the remix has \"ten times the bass\" of the original version.<ref name=\"PopAllStar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-listen-2645238027.html|title=100 Gecs' 'Ringtone' Remix Is a Pop All-Star Game|website=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|author=Brendan Wetmore|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225130948/https://www.papermag.com/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-listen-2645238027.html|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Patrick Johnson of ''Hypebeast'' described \"Ringtone (Remix)\" as sporadic and glitchy; Charli XCX sings the chorus on top of \"high-pitched vocal samples and [[1980s in video games|80's video game]]-inspired blips.\"<ref name=\"Hypebeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/2/100-gecs-rington-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kero-kero-bonito-listen|title=100 gecs Connect With Charli XCX, Rico Nasty and Kero Kero Bonito for \"ringtone\" Remix|website=Hypebeast|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Patrick Johnson|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405022825/https://hypebeast.com/2020/2/100-gecs-rington-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kero-kero-bonito-listen|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In her hook, Charli XCX is vulnerable, similar to her 2017 single \"[[Boys (Charli XCX song)|Boys]]\", though she sings about trading many boys for just the one.<ref name=\"p4k\"/>  The beat switches for Nasty's verse, who raps over an electric guitar and then sings with [[Auto-Tune]].<ref name=\"Hypebeast\"/> Les briefly chimes in to ask Charli XCX to sing the hook.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3157514/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|title=100 Gecs and Charli XCX Join Forces for a Delriously Fun 'Ringtone' Remix|website=[[MTV]]|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Madeline Roth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302231619/http://www.mtv.com/news/3157514/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n\"Ringtone (Remix)\" was first teased at a live DJ set by producer Umru on January 24, 2020.<ref name=\"Tease\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2071156/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kkb/video|title=Preview 100 gecs\u2019 \u201cRingtone\u201d Remix Feat. Charli XCX, Rico Nasty, & Kero Kero Bonito|website=[[Stereogum]]|date=January 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Chris DeVille|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129002204/https://www.stereogum.com/2071156/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kkb/video|archive-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The remix's existence became known after fan-captured footage of the DJ set was shared online.<ref name=\"Tease\"/> To provoke fans, Brady teased on [[Twitter]] that he had a third collaboration with Nasty on the way, after Nasty previously teased the song \"iPhone\" in November 2019.<ref name=\"Paper\"/> On February 21, 2020, New Zealander radio personality [[Zane Lowe]] of [[Apple Music]] interviewed 100 Gecs to discuss the recording of \"Ringtone (Remix)\" and ''1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/post/sa.95f47630-54ed-11ea-ac2b-f8c6ceb1d53f|title=Watch \"100 gecs on \"Ringtone (feat. Charli XCX, Rico Nasty, Kero Kero Bonito) [Remix]\"\" posted by New Music Daily with Zane Lowe on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|author=[[Zane Lowe]]|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405024116/https://music.apple.com/us/post/sa.95f47630-54ed-11ea-ac2b-f8c6ceb1d53f|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Ringtone (Remix)\" was officially released on February 24, 2020. The song was released with a visualizer video that features Brady and Les holding up stick puppets of the remix's guest features.<ref name=\"MTV\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nJillian Mapes of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' wrote that \"Ringtone (Remix)\" plays like a Charli XCX song with Rico Nasty serving in a featured artist role and Kero Kero Bonito providing supporting vocals.<ref name=\"p4k\"/> Mapes stated that the production is resemblant of [[PC Music]]'s work and predicted that the song would become an Internet hit.<ref name=\"p4k\"/> Brendan Wetmore of ''Paper'' praised the original version as one of the standout songs off of ''1000 Gecs'', but wrote that \"the addition of the all-star cast for new verses makes the remix a certified hit.\"<ref name=\"PopAllStar\"/> Madeline Roth of [[MTV]] wrote that Charli XCX is a \"natural fit for the gecs universe\" and praised Nasty's and Kero Kero Bonito's bubbly performances.<ref name=\"MTV\"/> Patrick Johnson of ''Hypebeast'' described Charli XCX's chorus as catchy.<ref name=\"Hypebeast\"/>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/130365575/credits|title=Credits / ringtone (Remix) [feat. Charli XCX, Rico Nasty, Kero Kero Bonito] / 100 gecs \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[100 Gecs]] \u2013 lead artist\n* [[Charli XCX]] \u2013 featured artist\n* [[Rico Nasty]] \u2013 featured artist\n* [[Kero Kero Bonito]] \u2013 featured artist\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Charli XCX}}\n{{Kero Kero Bonito}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:Charli XCX songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Charli XCX]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name     = Ringtone (Remix)\n| cover    = Ringtone Remix cover art.jpg\n| border   = \n| alt      = Dylan Brady and Laura Les wear black robes and hold a mirror.\n| type     = single\n| artist   = [[100 Gecs]] featuring [[Charli XCX]], [[Rico Nasty]] and [[Kero Kero Bonito]]\n| album    = [[1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues]]\n| released = {{Start date|2020|2|24}}\n| format   =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| length   = {{Duration|m=3|s=35}}\n| label    = Dog Show\n| chronology = [[100 Gecs]]\n| prev_title = 745 Sticky (Injury Reserve Remix)\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = gec 2 \u00dc (Remix)\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc = {{Extra chronology \n| artist = [[Charli XCX]]\n| type = single\n| prev_title = Bricks\n| prev_year = 2019\n| title = Ringtone (Remix)\n| year = 2020\n| next_title = [[Forever (Charli XCX song)|Forever]]\n| next_year = 2020}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = [[Rico Nasty]]\n| type = single\n| prev_title = IDGAF\n| prev_year = 2020\n| title = Ringtone (Remix)\n| year = 2020\n| next_title = Lightning\n| next_year = 2020\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = [[Kero Kero Bonito]]\n| type = single\n| prev_title = When the Fires Come\n| prev_year = 2019\n| title = Ringtone (Remix)\n| year = 2020\n| next_title = \n| next_year = \n}}\n{{External music video|header=Visualizer video|{{YouTube|OmX4UPiVS-w|\"Ringtone (Remix)\"}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Ringtone (Remix).ogg}}\n}}\n\"'''Ringtone (Remix)'''\" is a song by American experimental musical duo [[100 Gecs]], composed of Dylan Brady and Laura Les, from their upcoming remix album ''[[1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues]]'' (2020). The song features [[Guest appearance|featured vocals]] from British singer [[Charli XCX]], American rapper [[Rico Nasty]], and British indie pop band [[Kero Kero Bonito]]. The song is a remix of \"Ringtone\", a highlight from 100 Gecs' debut studio album ''[[1000 Gecs]]'' (2019). The song's production is glitchy with \"[[1980s in video games|80's video game]]-inspired blips\" and uses heavy [[Bass (sound)|bass]] and [[Auto-Tune]]. \n\n\"Ringtone (Remix)\" was first previewed at a live DJ set in January 2020. It was released a month later on February 24, 2020 as the third single from ''1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues'', following the release of the \"Money Machine\" and \"745 Sticky\" remixes. The song was met with critical acclaim, who praised Charli XCX's guest appearance.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Charlixcxnoodles.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Brady previously worked with British singer [[Charli XCX]] (pictured), whose guest appearance on \"Ringtone (Remix)\" was praised by critics.]]\n100 Gecs released their debut album, ''[[1000 Gecs]]'', on May 31, 2019. Jillian Mapes of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called the original version of \"Ringtone\" as a highlight from the album and \"among 100 Gecs' catchiest songs.\"<ref name=\"p4k\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-ft-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-and-kero-kero-bonito|title=\"ringtone (Remix)\" by 100 gecs Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Jillian Mapes|date=February 25, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229023901/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-ft-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-and-kero-kero-bonito|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Brady produced on British singer [[Charli XCX]]'s song \"[[Click (Charli XCX song)|Click]]\" featuring German singer [[Kim Petras]] and Estonian rapper [[Tommy Cash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/117418368/credits|title=Credits / Charli / Charli XCX \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> \"Click\" was included on Charli XCX's third studio album ''[[Charli (album)|Charli]]'', released on September 13, 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/46001/1/listen-to-charli-xcx-new-album-charli|title=It\u2019s here! Listen to Charli XCX\u2019s new album, Charli|website=[[Dazed]]|author=Gunseli Yalcinkaya|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401024956/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/46001/1/listen-to-charli-xcx-new-album-charli|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and was later rereleased as \"Click (No Boys Remix)\" that replaces Cash with American singer [[Slayyyter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8532958/charli-xcx-kim-petras-slayyyter-for-click-remix|title=Charli XCX Teams Up With Kim Petras & Slayyyter for 'No Boys' Remix of 'Click': Listen|author=October 14, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301194509/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8532958/charli-xcx-kim-petras-slayyyter-for-click-remix|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2019, 100 Gecs announced an upcoming remix album titled ''1000 Gecs & Th3 Phant0m M3nac3''.<ref name=\"AG\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/100-gecs-announce-new-remix-album-share-a-g-cook-money-machine-listen|title=100 gecs Announce New Remix Album, Share A. G. Cook\u2019s \"money machine\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Matthew Strauss|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229023905/https://pitchfork.com/news/100-gecs-announce-new-remix-album-share-a-g-cook-money-machine-listen|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A remix of \"Money Machine\" by British producer [[A. G. Cook]] was released alongside the announcement.<ref name=\"AG\"/> A. G. Cook is a frequent Charli XCX collaborator.<ref name=\"p4k\"/> On November 6, 2019, 100 Gecs released a remix of \"745 Sticky\" with American hip hop trio [[Injury Reserve]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/11/06/injury-reserve-remix-100-gecs-745-sticky|title=Listen to Injury Reserve\u2019s new remix of 100 gecs' \"745 Sticky\"|website=[[The Fader]]|author=Jack Denton|date=November 6, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211205826/https://www.thefader.com/2019/11/06/injury-reserve-remix-100-gecs-745-sticky|archive-date=December 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, American rapper [[Rico Nasty]] teased an upcoming collaboration with Brady titled \"iPhone\"; Nasty said in January 2020 that she'd release the song once American rapper [[Lil Uzi Vert]] recorded a verse for it.<ref name=\"Paper\">{{Cite web|url=http://papermag.com/dylan-brady-rico-nasty-track-2645128012.html|title=The Stans Demand Rico Nasty and Dylan Brady's Collabs|website=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|date=February 12, 2020|author=Brendan Wetmore|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311142024/https://www.papermag.com/dylan-brady-rico-nasty-track-2645128012.html|archive-date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Upon the release of \"Ringtone (Remix)\", the remix album was renamed ''1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/charli-xcx-and-rico-nasty-join-100-gecs-on-new-ringtone-remix-listen|title=Charli XCX and Rico Nasty Join 100 gecs on New \"ringtone (remix)\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Allison Hussey|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302195312/https://pitchfork.com/news/charli-xcx-and-rico-nasty-join-100-gecs-on-new-ringtone-remix-listen|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\"Ringtone (Remix)\" is less frenzied than its original counterpart and fits with Charli XCX's futuristic pop style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/stream-100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|title=Charli XCX and Rico Nasty Join 100 gecs on New \u201cringtone\u201d Remix: Stream|author=Lake Schatz|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225131914/https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/stream-100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Brendan Wetmore of ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' wrote that the remix has \"ten times the bass\" of the original version.<ref name=\"PopAllStar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-listen-2645238027.html|title=100 Gecs' 'Ringtone' Remix Is a Pop All-Star Game|website=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|author=Brendan Wetmore|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225130948/https://www.papermag.com/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-listen-2645238027.html|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Patrick Johnson of ''Hypebeast'' described \"Ringtone (Remix)\" as sporadic and glitchy; Charli XCX sings the chorus on top of \"high-pitched vocal samples and [[1980s in video games|80's video game]]-inspired blips.\"<ref name=\"Hypebeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/2/100-gecs-rington-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kero-kero-bonito-listen|title=100 gecs Connect With Charli XCX, Rico Nasty and Kero Kero Bonito for \"ringtone\" Remix|website=Hypebeast|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Patrick Johnson|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405022825/https://hypebeast.com/2020/2/100-gecs-rington-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kero-kero-bonito-listen|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In her hook, Charli XCX is vulnerable, similar to her 2017 single \"[[Boys (Charli XCX song)|Boys]]\", though she sings about trading many boys for just the one.<ref name=\"p4k\"/>  The beat switches for Nasty's verse, who raps over an electric guitar and then sings with [[Auto-Tune]].<ref name=\"Hypebeast\"/> Les briefly chimes in to ask Charli XCX to sing the hook.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3157514/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|title=100 Gecs and Charli XCX Join Forces for a Delriously Fun 'Ringtone' Remix|website=[[MTV]]|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Madeline Roth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302231619/http://www.mtv.com/news/3157514/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n\"Ringtone (Remix)\" was first teased at a live DJ set by producer Umru on January 24, 2020.<ref name=\"Tease\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2071156/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kkb/video|title=Preview 100 gecs\u2019 \u201cRingtone\u201d Remix Feat. Charli XCX, Rico Nasty, & Kero Kero Bonito|website=[[Stereogum]]|date=January 24, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|author=Chris DeVille|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129002204/https://www.stereogum.com/2071156/100-gecs-ringtone-remix-charli-xcx-rico-nasty-kkb/video|archive-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The remix's existence became known after fan-captured footage of the DJ set was shared online.<ref name=\"Tease\"/> To provoke fans, Brady teased on [[Twitter]] that he had a third collaboration with Nasty on the way, after Nasty previously teased the song \"iPhone\" in November 2019.<ref name=\"Paper\"/> On February 21, 2020, New Zealander radio personality [[Zane Lowe]] of [[Apple Music]] interviewed 100 Gecs to discuss the recording of \"Ringtone (Remix)\" and ''1000 Gecs & The Tree of Clues''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/post/sa.95f47630-54ed-11ea-ac2b-f8c6ceb1d53f|title=Watch \"100 gecs on \"Ringtone (feat. Charli XCX, Rico Nasty, Kero Kero Bonito) [Remix]\"\" posted by New Music Daily with Zane Lowe on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|author=[[Zane Lowe]]|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405024116/https://music.apple.com/us/post/sa.95f47630-54ed-11ea-ac2b-f8c6ceb1d53f|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Ringtone (Remix)\" was officially released on February 24, 2020. The song was released with a visualizer video that features Brady and Les holding up stick puppets of the remix's guest features.<ref name=\"MTV\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nJillian Mapes of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' wrote that \"Ringtone (Remix)\" plays like a Charli XCX song with Rico Nasty serving in a featured artist role and Kero Kero Bonito providing supporting vocals.<ref name=\"p4k\"/> Mapes stated that the production is resemblant of [[PC Music]]'s work and predicted that the song would become an Internet hit.<ref name=\"p4k\"/> Brendan Wetmore of ''Paper'' praised the original version as one of the standout songs off of ''1000 Gecs'', but wrote that \"the addition of the all-star cast for new verses makes the remix a certified hit.\"<ref name=\"PopAllStar\"/> Madeline Roth of [[MTV]] wrote that Charli XCX is a \"natural fit for the gecs universe\" and praised Nasty's and Kero Kero Bonito's bubbly performances.<ref name=\"MTV\"/> Patrick Johnson of ''Hypebeast'' described Charli XCX's chorus as catchy.<ref name=\"Hypebeast\"/>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/130365575/credits|title=Credits / ringtone (Remix) [feat. Charli XCX, Rico Nasty, Kero Kero Bonito] / 100 gecs \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[100 Gecs]] \u2013 lead artist\n* [[Charli XCX]] \u2013 featured artist\n* [[Rico Nasty]] \u2013 featured artist\n* [[Kero Kero Bonito]] \u2013 featured artist\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Charli XCX}}\n{{Kero Kero Bonito}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:Charli XCX songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Charli XCX]]\n", "name_user": "Nice4What", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ringtone_(Remix)"}
